(42, 5, 30, 44, 23, 9, 9, 'scribes and Pharisees', 'Scribes and Pharisees'' Opposition', 'This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between Jesus'' followers and the Pharisees. Both passages emphasize the role of the scribes and Pharisees in opposing those they deemed unworthy, whether it be Jesus'' association with sinners or their reaction to Paul.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 30, 23, 65, 5, 5, NULL, 'Critique of Holiness and Inclusion', 'This connection highlights the criticism of those who consider themselves ''holier than thou'' in Isaiah, paralleling the Pharisees'' disdain for Jesus'' association with ''publicans and sinners'' in Luke. Both passages emphasize a judgmental attitude towards others based on perceived righteousness.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 31, 41, 2, 17, 17, 'need not a physician', 'Connection of Healing and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the need for a physician for the sick, highlighting Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance. The phrase ''need not a physician'' appears in both, linking their messages about spiritual healing.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 31, 40, 9, 12, 13, 'They that are whole need not a physician', 'Connection of Healing and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the need for a physician for the sick, highlighting Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance. The reference to mercy in Matthew further connects the theme of healing and compassion for those in need.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 31, 24, 8, 22, 22, 'need not a physician', 'Healing and Restoration Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the need for healing, with Luke highlighting Jesus as a physician for the sick, while Jeremiah questions the absence of healing for the people. This connection highlights the theme of seeking restoration and the role of a healer.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 42, 19, 10, 10, 'sinners to repentance', 'Connection of Mission Statements', 'Both passages emphasize the mission of Jesus to reach out to those who are lost or in need of repentance. They highlight His purpose in seeking and saving sinners rather than the righteous.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 42, 15, 10, 10, 'sinners to repentance', 'Repentance and Joy in Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of repentance, as both passages focus on sinners turning back to God. Luke 5:32 emphasizes the call to sinners for repentance, while Luke 15:10 celebrates the joy in heaven over one sinner that repents.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 54, 1, 15, 16, 'sinners to repentance', 'Calling of Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the mission of Jesus to save sinners. Luke 5:32 states that Jesus calls sinners to repentance, while 1 Timothy 1:15 highlights that Christ came to save sinners, illustrating the same theme of mercy and redemption.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 44, 3, 19, 19, 'to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance', 'Call to Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of repentance. Luke 5:32 highlights the calling of sinners to repentance, while Acts 3:19 urges conversion for the blotting out of sins.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 23, 55, 6, 7, NULL, 'Call to Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the call for sinners to return to God and seek His mercy. Luke highlights Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance, while Isaiah encourages the wicked to forsake their ways and return to the Lord for pardon.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 44, 17, 30, 30, NULL, 'Call to Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of repentance. Luke 5:32 highlights Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance, while Acts 17:30 commands all men everywhere to repent, indicating a universal call for change.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 32, 61, 3, 9, 9, 'to repentance', 'Call to Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the call to repentance, highlighting God''s desire for sinners to turn back to Him. Luke 5:32 states that Jesus came to call sinners to repentance, while 2 Peter 3:9 expresses God''s longsuffering and willingness for all to come to repentance.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 40, 9, 14, 17, 'the disciples of John fast often', 'Fasting and Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the question of why the disciples of Jesus do not fast like those of John and the Pharisees. This connection highlights the contrast between the practices of fasting and the presence of Jesus, the bridegroom.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 41, 2, 18, 22, 'Why do the disciples of John fast', 'Fasting and Discipleship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the question of why Jesus'' disciples do not fast, contrasting them with the disciples of John and the Pharisees. This highlights a thematic exploration of the nature of fasting in relation to Jesus'' presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 42, 18, 12, 12, 'fast often', 'Fasting Practices in Luke', 'This connection highlights the theme of fasting practices among different groups. Both passages emphasize the act of fasting, with the first questioning why Jesus'' disciples do not fast like others, and the second describing a Pharisee who fasts regularly.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 42, 20, 47, 47, NULL, 'Fasting and Prayer Practices', 'This connection highlights the contrast between genuine spiritual practices and superficial displays of piety. Both passages emphasize the act of prayer, with the first questioning the sincerity of fasting and the second condemning long prayers for show.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 43, 3, 25, 25, 'fast often, and make prayers', 'Fasting and Purification Questions', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning practices related to fasting and purification. Both passages involve inquiries about the disciples'' behaviors, linking the act of fasting in Luke to the discussion of purification in John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 23, 1, 15, 15, NULL, 'Fasting and Prayer Contrast', 'This connection highlights the contrast between outward religious practices, such as fasting and prayer, and the inner moral state of individuals. Both passages emphasize the ineffectiveness of rituals when not accompanied by righteousness, as seen in the phrase ''make many prayers'' in Isaiah.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 33, 23, 58, 3, 6, 'fast', 'Fasting and True Worship', 'This connection highlights the contrast between superficial fasting and the true purpose of fasting. Both passages emphasize the need for genuine devotion rather than mere ritualistic practices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 43, 3, 29, 29, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Bridegroom Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the bridegroom, highlighting the joy associated with his presence. In Luke, the bridegroom''s presence signifies a time of celebration, while in John, the friend of the bridegroom rejoices at his voice.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 19, 45, 10, 16, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom and King', 'This connection highlights the imagery of a bridegroom and a king, where both passages emphasize a celebration of beauty and joy in the presence of the beloved. The reference to the bridegroom in Luke parallels the royal imagery in Psalms, suggesting a festive atmosphere surrounding both figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 22, 2, 6, 7, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of love and intimacy present in both passages. In Luke, the bridegroom''s presence signifies joy and celebration, while in Song of Solomon, the embrace symbolizes deep affection and longing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 22, 3, 10, 11, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom and Espousals', 'This connection highlights the theme of joy and celebration associated with a bridegroom and his espousals. Both passages emphasize a festive atmosphere, where the presence of the bridegroom signifies a time of gladness and love.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 23, 54, 5, 5, 'bridegroom', 'Bridegroom and Husband Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of a bridegroom and husband, both representing a relationship of intimacy and commitment. In Luke, the bridegroom''s presence signifies joy, while Isaiah refers to God as the husband, emphasizing His role as a protector and redeemer.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 23, 62, 5, 5, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the bridegroom and the bride. In Luke, the presence of the bridegroom signifies a time of joy, while Isaiah highlights God''s rejoicing over His people as a bridegroom does over his bride.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 34, 36, 3, 17, 17, 'while the bridegroom is with them', 'Joy and Presence of the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of joy in the presence of the Lord. In both passages, the presence of the bridegroom and the Lord brings joy and celebration, emphasizing the significance of divine companionship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 35, 42, 17, 22, 22, 'the days will come', 'Connection of Future Longing', 'Both passages emphasize a future time when the presence of the Son of Man will be absent, leading to a longing or desire for His return. This connection highlights the theme of anticipation and the emotional response of the disciples during that absence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 35, 43, 16, 4, 7, 'bridegroom shall be taken away', 'Connection of Sorrow and Departure', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow associated with the departure of the bridegroom or Jesus. Luke mentions that fasting will occur when the bridegroom is taken away, while John discusses the sorrow of the disciples as Jesus prepares to leave them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 35, 44, 3, 21, 21, 'the bridegroom shall be taken away', 'Connection of Fasting and Restitution', 'This connection highlights the theme of waiting for restoration after loss. In Luke, the absence of the bridegroom suggests a period of longing, while Acts speaks of the ''times of restitution'' that will follow. Both passages emphasize a future hope following a time of absence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 5, 35, 44, 14, 23, 23, 'then shall they fast in those days', 'Fasting in Response to Absence', 'This connection highlights the theme of fasting in response to the absence of the bridegroom, as seen in Luke 5:35. Acts 14:23 demonstrates the practice of fasting during significant moments in the early church, reflecting the ongoing need for spiritual reliance in the absence of Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
